{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17598818","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17598818"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:45:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:45:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15512"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15512","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15512"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.71,0.02,0.09,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8203"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61678"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8203","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8203"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15512"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47124"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1254"},{"type":"tags","id":"2545"},{"type":"tags","id":"2823"},{"type":"tags","id":"3801"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7882"},{"type":"tags","id":"9626"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19849"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19853"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61678","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/61678"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 12-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-day history of sore throat, fever, and headache. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His immunisations are up to date. On examination, he appears unwell with a pulse rate of 110/min, blood pressure 115/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. His throat is erythematous with enlarged, erythematous tonsils and tender anterior cervical lymphadenopathy. A rapid antigen test is positive for Group A Streptococcus.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most serious potential complication of untreated Group A Streptococcal pharyngitis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Peritonsillar abscess","Rheumatic fever","Scarlet fever","Otitis media","Cervical lymphadenitis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGroup A Streptococcal pharyngitis can lead to both suppurative (local) and non-suppurative (systemic) complications. Understanding these complications is crucial for appropriate management and follow-up.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERheumatic fever\u003C/strong\u003E is the most serious potential complication of untreated Group A Streptococcal pharyngitis. It is an autoimmune response that can cause permanent cardiac valve damage, particularly affecting the mitral valve. Prevention of rheumatic fever is one of the main reasons for treating streptococcal pharyngitis with antibiotics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeritonsillar abscess\u003C/strong\u003E (quinsy) is a suppurative complication that can develop when infection spreads beyond the tonsillar capsule. While serious and requiring urgent treatment, it generally does not cause long-term sequelae if appropriately managed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScarlet fever\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by a sandpaper-like rash and strawberry tongue. It occurs when the bacteria produce an erythrogenic toxin. While historically significant, with modern antibiotics it is usually self-limiting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOtitis media\u003C/strong\u003E can occur as a local spread of infection but is generally less severe than other complications and responds well to treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECervical lymphadenitis\u003C/strong\u003E is a common finding in acute infection rather than a true complication. It typically resolves with treatment of the primary infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther important complications not listed include post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis, which can occur even after appropriate antibiotic treatment, and retropharyngeal abscess. The key to preventing most complications is prompt recognition and appropriate antibiotic therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Group A Streptococcal pharyngitis can lead to both suppurative and non-suppurative complications.","Early recognition and treatment of streptococcal pharyngitis may prevent serious complications like rheumatic fever.","Post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis can occur even after appropriate antibiotic treatment."],"references":["Brouwer S, Rivera-Hernandez T, Curren BF, Harbison-Price N, De Oliveira DMP, Jespersen MG, Davies MR, Walker MJ. Pathogenesis, epidemiology and control of Group A Streptococcus infection. Nat Rev Microbiol. 2023 Jul;21(7):431-447. doi: 10.1038/s41579-023-00865-7. Epub 2023 Mar 9. Erratum in: Nat Rev Microbiol. 2023 Sep;21(9):619. doi: 10.1038/s41579-023-00939-6. PMID: 36894668; PMCID: PMC9998027.","Karthikeyan G, Guilherme L. Acute rheumatic fever. Lancet. 2018 Jul 14;392(10142):161-174. doi: 10.1016/S0140-6736(18)30999-1. Epub 2018 Jun 29. Erratum in: Lancet. 2018 Sep 8;392(10150):820. doi: 10.1016/S0140-6736(18)32057-9. PMID: 30025809.","Binotto M, Guilherme L, Tanaka A. Rheumatic Fever. Images Paediatr Cardiol. 2002 Apr;4(2):12-31. PMID: 22368613; PMCID: PMC3232519.","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47124"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15512"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47124","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/47124"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-16T11:17:13+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-16T11:18:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8203"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61678"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"cr